05349nam a22010455i 9780520928435DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696416  a97805209284357 a10.1525/97805209284352doi  a(DE-B1597)519437  a(OCoLC)437144829  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBS1825.52 4aBS1825.52 .J64 2004eb 7aREL0720002bisacsh04a229.75a229/.751 aJohnson, Sara Raup, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHistorical Fictions and Hellenistic Jewish Identity :bThird Maccabees in Its Cultural Context /cSara Raup Johnson. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (271 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHellenistic Culture and Society ;v4300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I. Historical Fictions And Hellenistic Jewish Identity -- tIntroduction Part I -- t1. Jews At Court -- t2. Josephus -- t3. Patriarchal Fictions -- tPart II. Third Maccabees: A Case Study -- tIntroduction Part II -- t4. Date, Literary Context, Authorship, And Audience -- t5. Historicity And Historical Ambivalence -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this thoughtful and penetrating study, Sara Raup Johnson investigates the creation of historical fictions in a wide range of Hellenistic Jewish texts. Surveying so-called Jewish novels, including the Letter of Aristeas, 2 Maccabees, Esther, Daniel, Judith, Tobit, Josephus's account of Alexander's visit to Jerusalem and of the Tobiads, Artapanus, and Joseph and Aseneth, she demonstrates that the use of historical fiction in these texts does not constitute a uniform genre. Instead it cuts across all boundaries of language, provenance, genre, and even purpose. Johnson argues that each author uses historical fiction to construct a particular model of Hellenistic Jewish identity through the reinvention of the past. The models of identity differ, but all seek to explore relations between Jews and the wider non-Jewish world. The author goes on to present a focal in-depth analysis of one text, Third Maccabees. Maintaining that this is a late Hellenistic, not a Roman, work Johnson traces important themes in Third Maccabees within a broader literary context. She evaluates the evidence for the authorship, audience, and purpose of the work and analyzes the historicity of the persecution described in the narrative. Illustrating how the author reinvents history in order to construct his own model for life in the diaspora, Johnson weighs the attitudes and stances, from defiance to assimilation, of this crucial period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHistorical fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aJewsxHistoryy586 B.C.-70 A.D. 0aJewsxIdentityxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh  a2 maccabees.  aacculturation.  aalienation.  aanti semitism.  aartapanus.  aassimilation.  abelonging.  adaniel.  adiaspora.  aesther.  aexile.  agenre studies.  ahellenistic judaism.  ahistorical adaptation.  ahistorical fiction.  ahomeland.  ajewish fiction.  ajewish identity.  ajewish literature.  ajewish migration.  ajewish novels.  ajewish world.  ajews and gentiles.  ajoseph and aseneth.  ajosephus.  ajudaica.  ajudaism.  ajudith.  alate hellenism.  aletter of aristeas.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary theory.  apersecution.  areligious difference.  athird maccabees.  atobiads.  atobit.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023307240uhtt